andards-university/" notes="Henning Larsen -  Syddansk Universitet communications and design building - {apos}Located just off the harbour in Kolding, the Syddansk Universitet communications and design building has a distinctive isosceles triangular shape that creates a highly visible new presence for the Danish university.{apos}{apos}Sensors monitor heat and light levels around the building, allowing the facade panels to shift from open to half-open to fully open. Even when fully closed, a controlled amount of natural light is able to shine through a custom pattern of round holes, some of which are linked to create amoeba-like openings.{apos}" text="Syddansk Universitet communications and design buildingno title">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="48" text="Light (Ext.)" weighting="0.3" xy="25461,24698">\n						<node example_instance="YES" id="165" link="INSTANCE">\n						</node>\n						<node color="#000000" date="2012" id="173" link="http://www.archdaily.com/270592/al-bahar-towers-responsive-facade-aedas" notes="Al-Bahr Towers, Aedas Architects, Abu Dhabi, UAE - {apos}For Abu Dhabi’s newest pair of towers, Aedas Architects have designed a responsive facade which takes cultural cues from the “mashrabiya”, a traditional Islamic lattice shading device.{apos}...{apos}The screen opperates as a curtain wall, sitting two meters outside the buildings’ exterior on an independent frame.  Each triangle is coated with fiberglass and programmed to respond to the movement of the sun as a way to reduce solar gain and glare.  In the evening, all the screens will close.\n\n“At night they will all fold, so they will all close, so you’ll see more of the facade.  As the sun rises in the morning in the east, the mashrabiya along the east of the building will all begin to close and as the sun moves round the building, then that whole vertical strip of mashrabiya will move with the sun,” said Peter Oborn, the deputy chairman of Aedas.{apos}" text="Al-Bahr Towers">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="49" text="Pollution" weighting="0.3" xy="25503,24802">\n					</node>\n					<node color="#000000" id="50" text="Wind" weighting="0.3" xy="25521,24918">\n						<node color="#000000" date="2011" id="174" link="" notes="Ned Khan, Children{apos}s Museum, Pittsburgh, USA - Dynamic, yet low-tech facade, thousands of hinged resin flaps move in the wind and created different light patterns in different lighting conditions, no computation involved" text="Children{apos}s Museum Pittsburgh">\n						</node>\n						<node color="#000000" date="2015" id="285" link="http://www.moduarchitecture.com/Cloud-Seeding-Holon-Design-Museum-Holon" notes="Motu Architecture, Cloud Seeding Pavillion, Holon, Israel - Plastic balls suspended between two transparent sheets create dynamic shadow effects on floor. Driven by the wind." text="Cloud Seeding Museum">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#000000" id="51" text="Sound\n" weighting="0.3" xy="25419,24980">\n					</node>\n				</node>\n			</node>\n			<node color="#00B439" id="52" text="Objects" weighting="0.6" xy="24885,24501">\n				<node color="#990000" id="53" text="Objects passing through" weighting="0.4" xy="25182,24951">\n					<node color="#111111" id="54" text="Tagged objects passing through, as in a warehouse. For example, restricting access to people, if a specific object is inside, which might be high value or dangerous. Or, automatically preparing the correct loading bay in a warehouse, because a delivery of particular items is due to arrive in the next 5 minutes." weighting="0.30000000000000004" xy="25406,25123">\n					</node>\n				</node>\n				<node color="#990000" id="55" text="Interaction objects - where the interaction with an object impacts on the building" weighting="0.4" xy="25191,24670">\n					<node color="#111111" date="2008" id="Freemind_Link_916986416" link="http://www.inqbate.co.uk" notes="The Centre of Excellence in Teaching and Learning in Creativity\n\nInQbate, The CETL in Creativity, is a joint initiative between the University of Sussex and the University of Brighton building on their excellent track record of collaborating in the areas of design, innovation and creativity. InQbate explores how a technology-rich environment can support the creative process, in both science and arts subjects.\n\nTwo Creativity Zones form the centrepiece of InQbate and offer exciting opportunities for students to work in spaces that foster collaborative, self-directed and experiential learning." text="InQbate">\n					</node>\n				</node>\n				<node color="#990000" id="56" text="Objects passing by" weighting="0.4" xy="25191,24814">\n					<node color="#111111" date="2007" id="Freemind_Link_87519176" link="http://research.gold.ac.uk/4781/" notes="Aeroplanes continuously transmit information about their journey, and these signals can be captured and decoded in the home. The Plane Tracker uses this data to visualise the imagined routes of individual flights, shown on screen as aerial imagery that flows smoothly from origin to destination. As you watch, you are able to vicariously experience the flights from the comfort of your front room. There’s no particular purpose in this - the design is not centred on any clear task or problem. Instead, we want to create a situation that highlights air travel, an issue about which different people (e.g. frequent travellers, environmental activists, plane spotters) might have different opinions." text="Plane Tracker">\n					</node>\n				</node>\n			</node>\n			<node color="#00B439" id="57" text="Scripting / Machine Learning" weighting="0.5" xy="24753,24666">\n				<node color="#990000" id="58" text="Driving adaptation from internal data and processes / Internal feedback loop" weighting="0.4" xy="25134,25084">\n					<node color="#111111" date="2008" id="ID_375190960" link="http://cita.karch.dk/Menu/Projects/Behaving Architectures (selection)/Slow Furl (2008)" notes="Mette Ramsgard Thommsen, Slow Furl, Copenhagen, Denmark, 2008" text="Slow Furl">\n					</node>\n				</node>\n			</node>\n		</node>\n		<node color="#0033FF" id="59" text="Effect        This branch details what the effect of adaptations is on (Logical data sink)." weighting="0.6" xy="24386,24085">\n			<node color="#00B439" id="60" text="Environment         defined by architecture (directly)" weighting="0.5" xy="24283,23871">\n				<node color="#990000" id="61" text="Light" weighting="0.4" xy="24013,23575">\n					<node color="#111111" id="216" text="Natural lighting" weighting="0.30000000000000004" xy="23739,23485">\n						<node color="#111111" date="1999" id="ID_1054322174" link="http://www.hopkins.co.uk/projects/2/90/" notes="Hopkins Architects, University of Nottingham, Jubilee Campus\n\nInternal shading blinds: At the beginning, these blinds were automatically controlled by the building infrastructure, while the purpose of the adjustment remained unclear. An override button allowed people to make their own adjustements. These were overriden by the building three times a day, until occupants removed the connections to the blinds. The blinds are now turned off (2015)." text="Jubilee Campus">\n						</node>\n						<node color="#000000" date="2016" id="100" link="http://www.archdaily.com/789230/let-your-building-to-breathe-with-this-pneumatic-facade-technology?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter" notes="Becker & Huffer, Breathing Skins, Stuttgart, Germany - Inflatables are mounted sandwiched between to transparent sheets of material. Low pressure in a panel expands all inflatables. This creates variations in incident light, air flow and views. - \n\nhttp://www.breathingskins.com/" text="Breathing Skins">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="217" text="Artificial lighting" weighting="0.30000000000000004" xy="23813,23589">\n						<node color="#111111" date="1999" id="ID_876699229" link="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110118095356/http:/www.cabe.org.uk/case-studies/jubilee-campus-nottingham-university" notes="Automatic lighting at Jubilee Campus, The University of Nottingham. A typical installation of lighting triggered by the presence of occupants to save energy." text="Automatic Lighting at Jubilee Campus">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="62" text="Light Temperature and level" weighting="0.3" xy="23718,23362">\n						<node example_instance="YES" id="Freemind_Link_916986416" link="INSTANCE">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n				</node>\n				<node color="#990000" id="63" text="Sound" weighting="0.4" xy="24036,23431">\n					<node color="#111111" date="1986" id="Freemind_Link_29077936" link="http://www.archdaily.com/344664/ad-classics-tower-of-winds-toyo-ito/" notes="Toyo Ito, Tower of Winds, Tokyo, Japan - By day the tower, clad in perforated aluminum panels, reflects the city through the reflective surfaces covering the steel core. The project is rather humble, literally reflecting the city through the complexity of its material. Come night time, the Tower of Winds takes a more pro-active role, translating sound and wind into light through two computers sensing the varying wind and noise levels and accordingly powering 1300 lamps, 12 neon rings, and 30 flood lights at its base. " text="Tower of Winds">\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="64" text="Sound quality" weighting="0.30000000000000004" xy="23715,23241">\n						<node color="#111111" date="1991" id="Freemind_Link_1534467951" link="http://www.tensinet.com/database/viewProject/3887" notes="FTL Design Engineering Studio, Carlos Moseley Music Pavillion, 1991, USA\n\nTransportable music stage and concert hall for outdoors that lets concert-hall quality sound be replicated whereever it is set up." text="Carlos Moseley Music Pavillion">\n						</node>\n					</node>\n					<node color="#111111" id="65" text="Sound Scape" weighting="0.30000000000000004" xy="23707,23135">\n						<node color="#111111" date="2004" id="Freemind_Link_12575322